Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows how to expose a C++ iterator over PCAP‑NG frames to Python so that a Python user can supply a callable that will be executed for every frame as the iterator walks the collection.

* The example uses **pybind11** (the modern, header‑only way to write CPython extensions).
* A tiny **mock implementation** of the libpcapng API is included so you can compile‑and‑run the example without pulling in the real library.  Replace the mock with the real headers / classes and the same binding will work.
* The Python‑facing API is deliberately “Pythonic”: the iterator is exposed as a normal Python iterator (`for frame in reader:`) **and** a convenience method `for_each(callback)` is provided for the exact use‑case you described.

---

## 1. Directory layout

```
pcapng_binding/
│
├─ CMakeLists.txt          # build script (works with pybind11 + CMake)
├─ pcapng.hpp              # tiny mock of the real libpcapng API
├─ binding.cpp             # the pybind11 glue (the only file you need to edit)
└─ test.py                 # example Python usage
```

---

## 2. Mock libpcapng header (`pcapng.hpp`)

> **NOTE** – In a real project you would `#include <libpcapng/pcapng.hpp>` (or whatever the real header is).  The mock below mimics the parts we need: a `Frame` struct and a `PcapngFile` class exposing `begin()`/`end()` iterators.

```cpp
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// pcapng.hpp  (mock – replace with the real libpcapng header)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
#pragma once
#include <cstdint>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <iterator>
#include <chrono>
#include <random>
#include <algorithm>

namespace libpcapng {

/// Simple representation of a captured frame.
struct Frame {
    std::uint64_t   timestamp_ns;   // Epoch time in nanoseconds.
    std::size_t     captured_len;   // Number of bytes actually captured.
    std::size_t     original_len;   // Length of the original packet on the wire.
    std::vector<std::uint8_t> data; // Raw bytes.

    // Helper to get the timestamp as a std::chrono::nanoseconds.
    std::chrono::nanoseconds timestamp() const {
        return std::chrono::nanoseconds(timestamp_ns);
    }
};

/// A tiny in‑memory PCAP‑NG file that can be iterated over.
class PcapngFile {
public:
    explicit PcapngFile(const std::string& filename) {
        // In a real implementation we would open and parse *filename*.
        // Here we just generate a few synthetic frames so the demo works.
        std::mt19937_64 rng{std::hash<std::string>{}(filename)};
        std::uniform_int_distribution<int> size_dist(64, 1500);
        std::uniform_int_distribution<int> delay_dist(0, 1'000'000); // ns

        std::uint64_t ts = 1'600'000'000'000'000'000ULL; // some epoch start

        for (int i = 0; i < 10; ++i) {
            Frame f;
            f.timestamp_ns = ts;
            f.captured_len = f.original_len = size_dist(rng);
            f.data.resize(f.captured_len);
            std::generate(f.data.begin(), f.data.end(),
                          [&rng]() { return static_cast<std::uint8_t>(rng() & 0xFF); });
            frames_.push_back(std::move(f));
            ts += delay_dist(rng);
        }
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    //  C++ style iterator (forward only, input iterator)
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    using iterator = std::vector<Frame>::const_iterator;

    iterator begin() const noexcept { return frames_.cbegin(); }
    iterator end()   const noexcept { return frames_.cend();   }

private:
    std::vector<Frame> frames_;
};

} // namespace libpcapng
```

